Simon,

Glad to hear from you!  (Read your article in DipPouch...)

Yes, I would be very interested in what was happening between the Great 
Powers in the dippouch game/bourse.

I was the 3rd largest holder of francs (behind Loeb and some other guy), 
with a side bet on Turkey (sold all other Great Power currency).

The game just kind of melted away over the winter break...the level of 
activity in the monthly buy/sell arena plummeted.  (The usual problem with 
our hobby; that a substantial fraction of players are students whose 
lives are dominated by the tides of the semester grade reports...)

Further, I think that many players did not fully grasp the mechanics of 
how the buy/sell orders were filled.  Many players accurately guessed the 
transaction price each month, but of course, the only players that got to 
actually trade currency were the ones with buy orders far above or sell 
orders far below the trade price.

Indeed, some players sent in sell orders and buy orders that were the 
stuff of fantasy.  "Hey, if someone wants to buy my English pounds at 
$1.50 each, I am more than glad to sell them!"  These people did not 
understand that even if someone actually did want to buy up English 
pounds (say they wanted a crack at taking over the helm of state), and 
offered $1.50 each, the players that would get the resulting inflated
sale price would be the ones with the _lowest_ selling price orders.  

This inability to understand what was needed to actually change ones 
portfolio from the inital distribution probably acted as an unseen 
barrier to continued involvement....critical mass in the market was not 
sustained.

But it was cool to read all the email traffic about the value of the 
"basket of currencies", the sophisticated ananlyses, and the broadcasts 
from the various members of the Russian Cabinet.

It took me a few turns to figure out how to actually get currency to 
change hands (see above).  After that, I decided that I would pick a 
horse and go with it (and a side bet).  The churning of the market 
business did not appeal to me...     The horse I picked was the 
designer of the bourse, Loeb, playing France, a strong Power.  Further, 
I had identified the Italian player as weak, from a previous game....

I vote FOR a further article on dippouch.  Maybe we could put it in a 
multi-layed TO: FROM: email loop that will bounce around between various 
internet nodes for 99 years or something before being read.  Sort of like 
a cyber time capsule.

So, how is your life?  I recall that you stepped down as master to move 
from SF to LA and get married?  But now, I see that you are in Pittsburgh
....hmmm.  Must be you are now in a PhD program?


Regards,
Chris Hoover
hoover@slac.stanford.edu


