Hello Frank,

You've hit upon something with your comment.

My ideas, naturally, did not arise in a vacuum. The bank-rank maurauder
idea is one that I've often discussed with one of my friends mentioned in
the article. Your point of view is essentially his own. Though he feels
that it's a powerful weapon, he also feels that it's the psychology, more
than the tactical threat, that ruins the other player's position. His own
opinon is the same as yours, i.e. "If that ever happens to me, I'll just
have one unit follow his around, taking the SC's as he jumps out of them,
until I can negotiate an end to the situation, or destroy the unit."

Real games, of course, are more complicated than that, but I agree that
it's a better baseline strategy for dealing with the situation than the
overcommitment of forces to stopping the invader. I suppose "how to handle
it if it happens to you" was a topic worth covering, had I thought of it.
Of course, the first bit of advice is "don't let it happen to you".

The nature of articles like this is to somewhat oversell your points (no
one is around to debate you after all). In reality, though, since the vast
majority of players will overreact, it's a great tactic to employ. Further,
it's the rare back rank maurauder that can't help you to strategic gains
well worth the cost, even if it's optimally dealt with.

Paul

P.S. I think I'll copy Manus into this exchange for consideration of
publication in the Pouch Deposits column.

