From: Frank Mayer <Frank.Mayer@darmstadt.netsurf.de>
To: pnkwindsor@msn.com
Subject: Caissa At The Diplomacy Table
Date: Monday, August 03, 1998 8:37 PM

Hi Paul,

I find both of your articles among the best I've encountered in the 'Zine
and find myself agreeing with almost all of what you say.

There is one point I am eager to get your opinion on. In your article you
wrote

The unit behind enemy lines is such an enormous distraction to the defender
that one must seriously consider placing it there, even if it has no hope
of
capturing a center. The threat posed by the mere presence of such a unit is
often sufficient to cause your enemy to assign two, three, or even four
units that were formerly on the attack to defensive maneuvers. The gain in
space or tempi that results is often well worth eventually losing the
lonely
maurader. I've never seen a position recover from the crippling effect of a
back rank maurauder.



and certainly, it is not unusual to see just such a panicked reaction to a
'line breaker', even among superior players. But, is it justified? You
argued so convincely elsewhere in your article that a good player should
consider the sacrfice of an SC to achieve a strategic goal. Why not accept
the unit behind the lines as an annoying fait accompli and avoid being
provoked into a disproportionate response. In the case you mentioned of
four
defenders seeking to hunt down and kill the marauder, this would mean using
just a single 'minder' constantly ordered to move to the marauder's
position, thereby limiting it's SC consumption potential to one and
preventing it from providing any support to new, would-be, line breakers..



I think you will find that the over-reaction of many players to a unit
behind the lines is a emotional response to terretorial imperatives and
can't be justified strategically.



Frank






