Kim/Paul Windsor wrote:

Hello Frank,
>
You've hit upon something with your comment.
>
My ideas, naturally, did not arise in a vacuum. The bank-rank maurauder
idea is one that I've often discussed with one of my friends ... His ..
opinon is ... "If that ever happens to me, I'll just
have one unit follow his around, taking the SC's as he jumps out of them,
until I can negotiate an end to the situation, or destroy the unit."
>
Real games, of course, are more complicated than that, but I agree that
it's a better baseline strategy for dealing with the situation than the
overcommitment of forces to stopping the invader. I suppose "how to handle
it if it happens to you" was a topic worth covering, had I thought of it.
Of course, the first bit of advice is "don't let it happen to you".

Paul,

I like your remark very much. You not only point out the role of emotional
reactions, but remind me not to expect consistent optimal play against from all
opponents. I'm sure you are right. If everyone played rationally all the time
there would be alot fewer wins.

You make alot of chess comparisons in your article and it occurs to me that
excellent chess players also deviate from assuming their opponents will play
optimally. For instance, if they know an opponent has had a history of
difficulty defending an isolated pawn, he will try to lead the game in that
direction. Something I've always wondered about (maybe you could tell me?) is
whether are there any computer chess programmes whose play varies according to
an opponents strengths and weaknesses?

Getting back to your article, I was a bit disappointed you didn't mention
anything about how the effectiveness of a marauder depends on the victim's
personality. Whereas an overly aggressive opponent might be provoked into an
over-reaction, a more phlegmatic victim, such as the friend you described,
could benefit from the assault, since, according to your concept, the
phlegmatic player will have devoted less time to defense than the marauding
power has dedicated in attack.

This brings me to some points I have been thinking about lately: the importance
of being about to read an opponent's personality; the importance of masking
your own personality; and the importance of having an arsenal of personality
driven procedures that can be flexibly implemented.

What I mean by 'personality' is any fairly consistent behaviour pattern. My
idea is that too consistent behaviour is debilitating. Firstly it makes our
actions predictable, and secondly it opens a window for manipulation.

For instance, if I meet you across the table and find out you have an ego with
a large appetite, I might be able to enslave you by providing that ego a high
protein diet. Once I feel confident of the behaviour of one or two players, I
can make educated guesses as to how they might continue and from which I can
then make long term plans. If I'm the only one that can plan far ahead this
would give me a big advantage over other players.

Another aspect I think important, because it confuses alot of people, is that
this has nothing to do with moral judgements as we usually understand them. It
makes no difference whether aplayer is predicatably generous or cowardly, as
long as he  is predictable. For this reason I think that the articles there
telling people how important it is to be a consistently trustworthy ally miss
the point. Being consistently anything isn't going to get you very far. What's
more important is to use disguised predictability to give the appearance of
harmlessness while knowing when and why to suddenly change behaviour.

Since my argument is that the effectiveness of tactics depends on the victim's
personality, it follows that a psychological profile of the players is needed,
and that we need a flexible set of manipulation techniques.

Lately I have begun putting together a technique table along these lines.
Here's an extract to show what I mean:


      Behaviour
      characteristic            Technique                 Desired result

                                                     Weakens ally's ability to
                           Near broadcast            solicit supporters by
 Fickle (ally)             announcement you have     making him seem
                           evidence of ally's        unsavoury. Hold moral
                           impending betrayal.       high ground for
                                                     'preemptive' stab.
                                                     Delay hostile stab
 Greedy (ally)             Control thru stories of   (especially useful if
                           Elyssian Fields
                                                     already near 18 SCs)
                           1. Encourage ally to lead
                           attack against bilious    Foe shows
                           foe. (This is especially  disproportionate hostile
 Temper (foe)              good if you have a greedy response against biggest
                           ally.)                    enemy, opening way for
                           2. Get unit behind the    opportunitistic gains.
                           lines.


One of the funniest things for me is how obvious this all looks once it's been
written down. Yet, in my experience, even players with a formidable intuitive
understanding of psychology haven't given much though to systematically
codifying their methods, and the exercise can be useful.

Well, what do you think?

frank




