Larry,
	I agree that a Chatroom is a good idea and would quickly fill
with dippers, but I'm not sure I like the ParaChat rooms.  Here are a few 
of the things I find less than ideally desirable about ParaChat:
	* Java interface requires graphical web browser
		As incompresensible as it may seem to us there are quite 
		a few people who have 'text-only' links to the Internet. 
		It would be nice to include them if possible (and it is)
	* Busy interface just doesn't look like the rest of the pouch.  
		Manus has been very careful and at times dictatorial in his
		effects to keep a uniform look across the pouch.  The big 
		block of chat just doesn't look like it belongs.
	* Advertisments
		The Dip Pouch has the distinction of being one of the few 
		truly good sites on the web that does not have advertisments.
		While I'm no loon saying that the profit motive is in any 
		way impure, I would just like to see any money that the 
		Pouch helps earn go to Manus, or .igo., or the hobby.

That said, all of these could be rememdies by giving money to parachat.  
Paying chat rooms are able to have an IRC (internet relay chat -- text 
based and generally superior interface) gateway.  Pay sites have mmore
control over what the room looks like, pay sites doen't get hit by 
advertisments.  
	The cost is $50-75 a month and that's just money I don't 
think the hobby should want to provide to someone outside the hobby.

Perhaps we should look for some free solutions that could be implemented 
locally.  I know that opensource message forums are plentiful and while 
they doen't offer the real-time satisfaction of chat, they are 
self-archiving and can breed some excellent discussion.  To see an 
example of forums at their finest check out http://slashdot.org .   
	Another possible solution is an IRC channel on a global IRC 
network.  These have the benifits of being accessible from all platforms 
and with all terminals, tons of 'getting started' help available, more 
configurable and more administration options.
	Who knows, maybe we can find a free/opensource version of a 
parachat style chatroom and can interface that with an IRC room.  What 
parachat is offering is the server/hosting their software isn't the 
service.  We've got a good server (www.diplom.org).

Showcase related:
	While the showcase has not been as active as it should be, it 
also has not been as dormant as it seems.  I've been working on a suite 
of scripts to generate full showcases from judge output.  As part of this 
undertaking I'm writing a Perl module to parse all manner of judge files, 
including:
	* list output
	* histories
	* results
	* map definitions
this data will be used to fill in standard datastrctures which can be 
read directly or accessed via provided methods.  It will be my goal to 
get this check into the CPAN (big perl library).
	All this work will occur to the great displesure of Manus who is 
a Python fan. 
	Also I will probably be putting up the bulk of the showcase for 
'gauntlet' this week.

--  
Ry4an Brase - http://acm.cs.umn.edu/~ry4an - 612-623-9946
'If you're not a rebel when you're 20 you've got no heart; if
 you're  not establishment when you're 30 you've got no brain.'



