>I can't put the old system back up because the whole reason
>the thing came down was because when Doug Massey sent in 1100+ games
>from old HOF records, my code choked and brought the machine to its
>knees.  I could spend some time fixing the code so it wouldn't choke,
>but I haven't had the time and now that there's a new effort, I'll
>probably let them do the work instead of me.  :-)
>
>Manus

Manus,

I've been so busy, I didn't even realize there was a new Pouch issue
available.  Looks like it is chock-full of good stuff.  However, I just
read the article on the new rating system and while I am reluctant to
criticize people who are making an effort to contribute to the hobby, I
feel there are some issues with the proposed system that I must object to.

1) Philosophy: I've always felt that an ELO-like system won't work very
well in Diplomacy.  In chess, it is one on one and a player has no one but
himself to blame if he loses.  In Dip, even the strongest player can be
eliminated quite easily if his opponents gang up on him.  Thus, it seems
unfair to extract a large penalty if those opponents have lower ratings.
Worse, from a practical standpoint a highly-rated player would be pretty
much restricted to gunboat games.  Currently, a player with a strong
reputation can still play in non-gunboat games.  Sure, some players will
try to wipe him out because they fear his rep, but others will want to team
up with him  for the same reason so it all balances out.  Now, players will
have an incentive to destroy a high-rated player, an incentive that has
nothing whatsoever to do with the game itself.  That is bad.

2) Abandonments: I don't really understand the system here, so my comments
are more general.  If I understand it correctly, a player who picks up a
position does not have his rating affected.  That is good and bad.  A
player who picks up a position should never be penalized.  To do so makes
no sense and would offer a strong disincentive to picking up mercy
positions.  But I believe a player should be rewarded if he is able to make
something of a pickup.  Why not?  Especially if he is picking up a position
very early in the game.  Not allowing a player to gain seems to offer a
strong disincentive to picking up positions abandoned in 1902.  Which
brings me to my next point.  As I said, I don't really understand the
formula offered for rating players who abandon, but the author states that
"It is not the place of an ability rating system to hurt the undedicated
however annoying they are but I don't think they can benefit either." which
leads to believe that a player may suffer less from abandoning a position
than playing it out or at least not be any worse off.  Either way, you may
find that players who care about nothing but ratings may tend to abandon at
the end of the first year if things don't go well.  In my opinion, a rating
system should offer incentives to pick up positions and disincentives to
abandon.

3) Press Options: Once again, I don't really understand the math (hey,
college was a long time ago!), but the sense of it seems to be that partial
is more meaningful than broadcast-only which is more meaningful than
no-press with real-time at the bottom of the stack (what about real-time
with press?).  The author does not give any rationale for this decision, so
it is difficult to comment.  I've found all sorts of different press
options to be challenging in different ways, but usually stick to
broadcast-only and no-press due to time constraints.  I don't see why they
should be rated any differently than other games, but if the author
believes they should be, it would seem more logical to have separate rating
lists for different press options.  Mind you, I am not advocating that
approach.  I'd much rather see the press options left out of calculations.
The same goes for time limits (ie., real-time).  If a system does not
reward a player for sheer volume of games played (and it shouldn't), then
what difference does it make how fast a game is played?  As with press
options, it seems to me that it is just a different set of challenges.

4) Short-Center Variants: It is possible that the designers of this system
simply did not think about variants where the winning centers are set very
low, but there does not seem to be any provision for treating them
differently.  It seems to be that a game with the winning centers set to
seven or fourteen, etc, while a perfectly legitimate variant, is
substantially different from a game where a player must capture a majority
of the centers to win.  This may be an unreasonable bias on my part, but I
think it something that should be considered.

5) Simplicity: Nothing profound here, just an observation that EIDRaS is a
very complicated system.  I prefer a simple system where I can easily
figure out how a result will affect my rating.  I suspect many players feel
the same way.

All of which brings me to the rating system that was in effect when the
system crashed.  It was a simple concept.  Each starting player risked one
rating point.  Replacements could gain points, but could never lose them.
The winners got back their ante and divided up the spoils from the losers.
It seemed to me that this system offered proper incentives (good to pick up
positions, no advantage whatsoever to dropping them, and no incentive to go
after a player simply because he is highly rated).  It also could easily be
applied to variants because the more players in a variant, the more rating
points were available.  Best of all, it was very simple.  At the end of the
day, the points gained equalled the points lost (an important modification
from the original YARS system).  And you never had to wonder how a game
would affect your rating.

The only disadvantage to this system that I can think of is that a player
can achieve a high rating by beating up patsies on a regular basis.  I'm
not really sure that this is a  serious problem though.  First of all, I
think strong players want the challenge of playing other strong players.
Secondly if there were enough cripple-shooters to be a problem, it could
easily be remedied by using (or expanding) the ranking system already in
place.  Currently, players self-rate themselves as Novice, Intermediate, or
Expert and games can be restricted to certain levels.  It is not a very
effective system especially since almost everyone starts off at Novice and
never gives another thought to changing it as they improve.  There could be
two approaches here.  Players with more than seven games completed could be
automatically categorized based on where they rank against other players
(top third are Experts, middle third Intermediate, bottom third Novice) or
games could be restricted based on rating (only open to players above zero
or below zero, etc).  It seems to me that overcoming this one problem can
be done without throwing out the baby with the bath water.

Lastly, I am sure this letter sounds very negative and, as I said, I am
reluctant to criticize anyone who is willing to work at improving the
hobby.  So, I do salute the people involved in this effort and appeciate
all the work that has gone into it.  But I really do believe that it is a
step in the wrong direction.

Regards,
Jeff Serandos

