Manus, I have launched an EIDRaS web site with a slight update to
the math dealing with abandonners and a hopefully better explanation why
replacements don't score anything. If you get more questions and are feeling
lazy you can direct them to
http://freespace.virgin.net/anthony.nichols/eidras.htm
The first ratings are also up.

 Jeff, in case you are wondering Manus passed your e-mail on to me to
respond.


1) Philosophy: I've always felt that an ELO-like system won't work very
well in Diplomacy.  In chess, it is one on one and a player has no one but
himself to blame if he loses.  In Dip, even the strongest player can be
eliminated quite easily if his opponents gang up on him.  Thus, it seems
unfair to extract a large penalty if those opponents have lower ratings.

 This could be read as a criticism of rating players in general, that
somethings
you lose without deserving to and sometimes you win without deserving
to. If you believe this I suggest you take no note of any ratings. I feel if
there are to be ratings they should at least be meaningful, hence I designed
(with a lot of help) eidras.

Worse, from a practical standpoint a highly-rated player would be pretty
much restricted to gunboat games.  Currently, a player with a strong
reputation can still play in non-gunboat games.  Sure, some players will
try to wipe him out because they fear his rep, but others will want to
team
up with him  for the same reason so it all balances out.  Now, players
will
have an incentive to destroy a high-rated player, an incentive that has
nothing whatsoever to do with the game itself.  That is bad.



What is the incentive to destroy a higher rated player exactly? My guess is
that you think taking the highest rated player out will help your rating
more
than taking out someone else. This is entirely wrong, your rating change
is solely dependent on your score(no of players divided by number of
winners)
and your expected score, which is determined before the game begins.
Who you share a draw with does not affect your rating, this would indeed
be unacceptable. Hence the only incentive to attack the best opponent is
what it has always been, that he represents the greatest threat.

>> 2) Abandonments: I don't really understand the system here, so my
comments
>> are more general.  If I understand it correctly, a player who picks up a
>> position does not have his rating affected.  That is good and bad.  A
>> player who picks up a position should never be penalized.  To do so makes
