rating
>> system should offer incentives to pick up positions and disincentives to
>> abandon.


Please check out the new website,
http://freespace.virgin.net/anthony.nichols/DP_eid.html
In my opinion EIDRaS does discourage abandoning but only mildly, it
certainly
offers no incentive. We designed EIDRaS to be an ability rating system and
to rank ability as accurately as possible given limited data. I don't want a
rating
system that rates ability and how many games you can cram in
(like YARS and HOF), nor one that rates ability and how many decent
abandoned
positions you can find and takeover. EIDRaS just rates ability. This is what
an
ability rating system should do. If you want a system to encourage
replacements
then design something yourself.

>> 3) Press Options: Once again, I don't really understand the math (hey,
>> college was a long time ago!), but the sense of it seems to be that
partial
>> is more meaningful than broadcast-only which is more meaningful than
>> no-press with real-time at the bottom of the stack (what about real-time
>> with press?).  The author does not give any rationale for this decision,
so
>> it is difficult to comment.

The K factor is there to determine to what degree the extra information that
game result presents improves the accuracy of that players rating. Different
K values determine how rapidly a player moves from his current rating
estimate to a more reasonable value, so having different Ks does not
penalise no-pressers with lower ratings just require more games to reach an
accurate rating. This represents the fact the players in full press must
devote
more time and effort and hence often get less games in per unit time and
generally full press allows more diplomacy skills to be displayed. One way
of viewing the earlier replacement question is this, acting as replacement
the result does not increase the accuracy of the players rating at all,
because
the strength of the initial position cannot be determined by formulaic means
or
other, hence K=0 for replacements.

>> 4) Short-Center Variants: It is possible that the designers of this
system
>> simply did not think about variants where the winning centers are set
very
>> low, but there does not seem to be any provision for treating them
>> differently.  It seems to be that a game with the winning centers set to
>> seven or fourteen, etc, while a perfectly legitimate variant, is
>> substantially different from a game where a player must capture a
majority
>> of the centers to win.  This may be an unreasonable bias on my part, but
I
>> think it something that should be considered.


 There are surely many areas where more thought on my behalf is required,
the Pouch article was very rushed, in that it come out almost immediately
on the back of initial rating systems discussions on r.g.d. I think, for
similar
arguments to the above, short variants will get smaller K values, also for
tournment games with such scoring systems. For now I am concentrating
on getting full games into the EIDRaS system before dealing with the more
rare games.

>> 5) Simplicity: Nothing profound here, just an observation that EIDRaS is
a
>> very complicated system.

 Not really it is the simpliest system that accurately rates ability, thats
why we
are using it. Most of the complexity come from abandonments and things
with are in all systems although they may not be described in such detail.

>> I prefer a simple system where I can easily
>> figure out how a result will affect my rating.  I suspect many players
feel
>> the same way.


Maybe, but is this good. Understanding the system is but a small step from
playing the system, especially were the system is too simple and hence
flawed.
Not understanding leaves you only able to play the game. Not even I
understand the system well enough to take advantage to enhance ratings.
Remember HOF and to a lesser extent YARS both encouraged playing lots
of games and taking no care of ones that started going badly so you had time
to start more. This was virtually required if you were half decent but
wanted
to get in the top 10 or whatever. All EIDRaS encourages is you take best
care
in every game you start and try to get the best possible result from it.
So even in philosophy EIDRaS encourages good practice.

>> All of which brings me to the rating system that was in effect when the
>> system crashed.  It was a simple concept.  Each starting player risked
one
>> rating point.  Replacements could gain points, but could never lose them.

>> The winners got back their ante and divided up the spoils from the
losers.
>> It seemed to me that this system offered proper incentives (good to pick
up
>> positions, no advantage whatsoever to dropping them, and no incentive to
go
>> after a player simply because he is highly rated).  It also could easily
be
>> applied to variants because the more players in a variant, the more
rating
>> points were available.  Best of all, it was very simple.  At the end of
the
>> day, the points gained equalled the points lost (an important
modification
>> from the original YARS system).  And you never had to wonder how a game
>> would affect your rating.


 OK thats your view, in my opinion the ratings were meaningless because they
confused player ability and number of games entered. As my article says
someone
with a slightly negative rating could be a prolific above average player or
an infrequent
appaling player. I ask simply what is the point of knowing that. There are
differences
between diplomacy and chess, but I think it is illustrative to consider what
rating
systems would look like in chess. Who would be top rated under
HOF?  - The most prolific blitz club player
YARS? - The guy who played a lot, probably against schoolkids he was
teaching the game.
ELO? - Gary Kasparov.

 Now answer me again, want was the point of HOF or YARS when the
best players don't get a look in.

 Cheers,

 Tony Nichols

