How'd you like the story?
>
Uh, well, I haven't read it yet.  I "b"ounced it over to The Pouch, so I 
no longer have it.  I probably won't read it until I edit the next issue
(coupla weeks) unless I get a surprise few minutes of free time.

As for judge play, I am a big fan of it.  True, I've never really played
PBEM otherwise, but to me, the judges are the way to go.  I think they
take a lot of heat from people who come to them wanting to find something
wrong with them.  Everyone in the postal community, for example, says that
the judges suck because their abandonment rate is so high.  I haven't
subscribed to very many postal 'zines (after all, I'm a PBEM'er!) but I
get them for free, just for being nice I guess :-) and frankly, I think
abandonment in the postal world is as bad or worse.  As for PBEM human vs.
PBEM judge, I've never done human, but even if I had, I would say I like
the judge better.  The judge is ALWAYS there to answer your questions.
The judge doesn't care if you change your orders a jillion times, and will
always politely tell you what they are.  The judge keeps track of forwarding
all your mail correctly.  You don't need to either remember a bunch of e-mail
addresses for the different powers or rely on the human GM to forward
your mail for you when he gets to a terminal.  The judge output feeds into
all the map making programs, so I can see a map onscreen anytime I want,
etc., etc.  IMHO, you just can't beat the judges.  I think they're even
better than FTF (but that's a close call, especially when talking about
FTF at the big conventions like the world championships, etc.)

Manus

